        "id": 282473,
        "name": "Timon Ehlers",
        "username": "TimonEhlers",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/d9b06d/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2026-01-10T10:40:17.386Z",
        "cooked": "<p>One of the most important aspects of accessibility is contrast. The maximal contrast is between black and white.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately the messages you receive are black on grey and not black on white. (The sent messages in blue are even worse, but less critical, because they are the messages you self typed.)</p>\n<p>WhatsApp and Telegram are doing better: received messages are black on white.</p>\n<p>I would suggest (for light-mode):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>received messages should be black on white</li>\n<li>sent messages should be black on a very light grey (it’s less contrast, but better than the blue background and less critical because they are your own messages)</li>\n<li>to distinguish the message-bubbles from the background, the background could be in a darker grey or (matching Signal’s corporate-identity) in a light blue. That would also be less obtrusive to the eyes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Alternative (also for light-mode):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>received messages also black on white</li>\n<li>sent messages on a light-blue background instead the dark-blue</li>\n<li>background in light-grey (similar like in WhatsApp)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In dark-mode you need other color-schemes, to be dark enough. But it could have an option to only darken the background and still keep the message-bubbles black-on-white for received messages and black-on-light-grey (alternative 1) or black-on-light-blue (alternative 2) for sent messages. (Because positive contrast (dark on light) is better for many people than negative contrast (light on dark).)</p>\n<p>That would improve the legibility significantly - not only for users with low vision, but for all users, because accessibility is crucial for people who need them, but all others benefit from it to, because it means less cognitive-workload and better visibility. (And when getting older, the eyes of all people are getting worse.)</p>\n<p>(And yes, I know, that you can change the colors of sent messages. But the received-messages are staying grey. And also the most accessible design should be default. If you prefer a less accessible design to match your own preferences, it’s OK to offer this in settings. But the default should be the most accessible design.)</p>",
